  "prompt": "How do you treat poison ivy in your mouth? What are some risks?",
  "response": "Treating poison ivy exposure in the mouth is urgent and requires immediate medical attention due to the potential risks and complications. Here are the steps and considerations:\n\n### Immediate Steps:\n1. **Rinse your mouth:** Rinse your mouth with plenty of water to help remove any urushiol oil (the substance that causes the reaction) that may be present.\n2. **Do not swallow:** Avoid swallowing the water used for rinsing, as it can spread the urushiol oil further into your digestive system.\n3. **Seek medical attention:** Contact a healthcare provider or go to an emergency room as soon as possible. Poison ivy in the mouth can cause severe allergic reactions and swelling, which may obstruct breathing.\n\n### Medical Treatment:\n- **Corticosteroids:** Doctors may prescribe corticosteroids to reduce inflammation and allergic reactions. These can be administered orally or through injection, depending on the severity.\n- **Antihistamines:** Over-the-counter or prescription antihistamines might be recommended to alleviate itching and swelling.\n- **Pain relief:** Pain relief medications may be advised to manage discomfort.\n\n### Risks:\n1. **Breathing difficulties:** Swelling in the mouth and throat can obstruct airways, leading to difficulty breathing which can be life-threatening.\n2. **Infection:** Open sores or blisters in the mouth can become infected.\n3. **Severe allergic reaction:** Anaphylaxis is a severe allergic reaction that may occur, necessitating immediate medical intervention.\n4. **Spread of the rash:** The rash can spread to other areas inside the mouth, throat, esophagus, and digestive tract.\n\n### Prevention:\n- **Avoid contact:** Learn to identify poison ivy to avoid contact.\n- **Wash thoroughly:** If you suspect exposure, wash the affected area with soap and water as soon as possible.\n\n### Conclusion:\nDue to the serious risks associated with poison ivy exposure in the mouth, prompt medical attention is crucial. Self-treatment is not recommended beyond initial rinsing; professional medical care is necessary to manage symptoms and prevent complications.",
